[1] England (Northumbria)
Date: Mon 3 Jun 2019 09:32 BST
Source: Northumberland Gazette [edited]
https://www.northumberlandgazette.co.uk/health/cases-of-whooping-cough-are-first-for-nhs-trust-1-9800077


Last year [2018], 2 cases of whooping cough were identified by Northumbria Healthcare -- the 1st in its history and attributed to 'waning vaccination rates'. They were reported by Dr David Tate, director of infection prevention and control, as he presented his annual report for 2018-19 to the latest board meeting of the trust, which runs hospitals in Northumberland and North Tyneside.

The 2 unrelated incidents, which were also the 1st Dr Tate had seen in his career, were in November 2018 and March this year [2019], with one affecting a baby.

In response to a question from a board member, he said that Public Health England recognises that work needs to be done on the issues around social media and its impact on falling vaccination rates. However, there were a number of positives, with Dr Tate concluding: "There's nothing I'm particularly concerned about, but obviously infection control is a constant and ongoing battle."

[Byline: Ben O'Connell]

